- Full HTTP request path: /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable? No. The code defines only GET and POST handlers for this path:
  - GET /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas (getConsumerPrintingSchemas)
  - POST /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas (addNewConsumerPrintingSchema)

- HEAD: Not defined in code for this path. Therefore, based on the code, HEAD is not acceptable.

- POST: Yes. There is a POST mapping for this path implemented by addNewConsumerPrintingSchema.

- OPTIONS: Not defined in code for this path. Therefore, based on the code, OPTIONS is not acceptable.

- TRACE: Not defined in code for this path. Therefore, based on the code, TRACE is not acceptable.

- GET: Yes. There is a GET mapping for this path implemented by getConsumerPrintingSchemas.

- PUT: Not acceptable for this base path. PUT is defined on /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}, not on /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas.

- DELETE: Not acceptable for this base path. DELETE is defined on /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}, not on /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas.

- PATCH: Not defined in code for this path. Therefore, based on the code, PATCH is not acceptable.

Explanation:
The PrintingSchemaController declares two @RequestMapping entries for the path /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas:
- GET mapped to getConsumerPrintingSchemas
- POST mapped to addNewConsumerPrintingSchema

No other HTTP methods are mapped to this base path. Other operations (PUT/DELETE) exist only on the extended path /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}, and there are no explicit HEAD/OPTIONS/TRACE/PATCH mappings for the base path. Consequently, only GET and POST are supported on /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas, and the other methods are not defined by this code.
